at a distance, when

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:05.850
Nicholas and I went to my
country of origin, Columbia.

00:03:05.850 --> 00:03:08.430
And developed what is considered
to be the most

00:03:08.430 --> 00:03:11.100
important education at a
distance project ever done in

00:03:11.100 --> 00:03:12.380
Latin America at that time.

00:03:12.380 --> 00:03:14.420
It was 32 years ago.

00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:20.130
And the final push for action
for me, which has prompted me

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:25.090
to continue all my life in the
current realm dedicated to

00:03:25.090 --> 00:03:28.000
this project is, that I have
lost these three children of a

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.650
very rare disease.

00:03:29.650 --> 00:03:30.700
Of a heart condition.

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:34.390
And my only concern right now
is how to leave the children

00:03:34.390 --> 00:03:38.860
of the world a little bit of a
legacy that I hoped I could

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:41.020
have left for my
three children.

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:44.150
And therefore it's a combination
of a professional

00:03:44.150 --> 00:03:45.700
friendship with Nicholas.

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:48.550
The dedication to study
and education.

00:03:48.550 --> 00:03:53.400
And my personal family life.

00:03:53.400 --> 00:03:54.750
How this whole thing started?

00:03:54.750 --> 00:03:57.020
Believe it or not this whole
thing started for us when we

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.890
started looking at this in my
country of origin, Columbia.

00:03:59.890 --> 00:04:03.920
In 1948 there was a very major
discovery or invention called

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:05.760
the transistor radio.

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:09.900
Well a priest in the forgotten
lands of the Altiplano of

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:14.820
Bogota, saw this little
invention and immediately saw

00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:19.310
the connection between that
little gadget and technology.

00:04:19.310 --> 00:04:22.130
And immediately put into every
peasant in the region.

00:04:22.130 --> 00:04:24.900
At the end there were more than
four and a half million

00:04:24.900 --> 00:04:28.880
peasants, a transistor radio in
the pocket of their shirts

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:31.780
while they were still plowing
the land with oxen and very

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:33.230
primitive ways.

00:04:33.230 --> 00:04:36.730
And in order to that he created
a radio station that

00:04:36.730 --> 00:04:39.415
was emblematic for 40 years
in Colombia, called Radio

00:04:39.415 --> 00:04:41.090
Sutatenza, Radio Sutatenza.

00:04:41.090 --> 00:04:43.990
It transmitted constantly,
while the

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:46.750
peasants and their wives--

00:04:46.750 --> 00:04:48.980
were at home-- and the peasants
in the field,

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:52.030
constant programs on
how to improve the

00:04:52.030 --> 00:04:52.990
conditions of the soil.

00:04:52.990 --> 00:04:54.970
The conditions of
the household.

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:58.970
How to boil water, how to do the
most incredible primitive

00:04:58.970 --> 00:05:01.410
ways that for us were
taken for granted.

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:03.710
But for them were nonexistent.

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:07.470
This priest educated four
and a half million

00:05:07.470 --> 00:05:08.810
peasants in that way.

00:05:08.810 --> 00:05:10.940
Alvin Toffler in his book,
"The Third Wave" and "The

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:13.000
Future Shock" visited
with him.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.810
It was very important at that
time how to use technology in

00:05:16.810 --> 00:05:20.290
education and improvement
of social conditions.

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:24.530
The pedagogical side is
these two gentlemen.

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:26.150
It's Jean Piaget from
Switzerland.

00:05:26.150 --> 00:05:31.690
And our own Seymour Papert,
South African mathematician

00:05:31.690 --> 00:05:35.870
who went to MIT in 1967 after
having worked with Jean Piaget

00:05:35.870 --> 00:05:37.170
for 15 years.

00:05:37.170 --> 00:05:41.030
And they saw that people that
wrote code or programs

00:05:41.030 --> 00:05:43.850
developed something, that for
you might be taken for granted

00:05:43.850 --> 00:05:46.740
right now, a very special
condition of the brain.

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:51.470
And that people who wrote
code could have a better

00:05:51.470 --> 00:05:54.310
understanding of critical
thinking.

00:05:54.310 --> 00:05:56.950
Of solution oriented
mentality.

00:05:56.950 --> 00:05:57.790
Of sharing.

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:00.370
And of reflection.

00:06:00.370 --> 00:06:02.300
Those four issues were
very important.

00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:06.840
So Seymour in 1967 arrives at
MIT to start the Artificial

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:08.330
Intelligence Lab.

00:06:08.330 --> 00:06:13.350
And he has the honesty and the
audacity of telling that every

00:06:13.350 --> 00:06:16.330
child in the future should have
a computer and be able to

00:06:16.330 --> 00:06:16.860
write code.

00:06:16.860 --> 00:06:19.630
At that time the computer was
larger than this building.

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:21.810
Everybody thought that
this guy was crazy.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:24.770
But Nicholas saw him, when
Nicholas was already after

00:06:24.770 --> 00:06:29.700
graduating from architecture,
and told him listen, far from

00:06:29.700 --> 00:06:32.280
believing that you're crazy
what I think that you are

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:33.660
doing is great.

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:35.930
Because what I'm trying to do
is create a graphical user

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:38.310
interface for us,
poor architects.

00:06:38.310 --> 00:06:43.050
That we're the last architects
that are still working with

00:06:43.050 --> 00:06:44.950
square Ts and triangles.

00:06:44.950 --> 00:06:46.160
And pencils.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:48.950
So they got together and that
became an association that

00:06:48.950 --> 00:06:54.310
lasted for almost 40 years
because Seymour now is almost

00:06:54.310 --> 00:06:55.900
90 years of age.

00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:58.270
And that's with Nicholas at one
of the last meetings that

00:06:58.270 --> 00:06:59.670
they were together.

00:06:59.670 --> 00:07:03.690
And so that prompted us to say,
we need to do something.

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:07.380
We need to try to bring the
new technologies into

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:10.990
educations in similar fashion,
as the transistor radio and

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:14.390
radio station were brought
at the time in 1948.

00:07:14.390 --> 00:07:17.420
And it is not difficult to
understand because if you take

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:20.330
into consideration that the
transistor radio of the time

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:21.710
is today a laptop.

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:25.130
And a radio station of that
time, today is the internet.

00:07:25.130 --> 00:07:27.540
Then immediately you can see
the similarities and the

00:07:27.540 --> 00:07:30.430
symbolisms that are present
in this type of concept.

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:32.160
So we didn't invent anything.

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:35.640
We just tried to advance a
concept that we knew had

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:38.760
worked very well for four and
a half million peasants.

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:41.450
And try to scale it
up to the rest of

00:07:41.450 --> 00:07:43.680
the developing nations.

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:50.130
So we needed to then decide
that we needed to

00:07:50.130 --> 00:07:52.390
differentiate learning
from education.

00:07:52.390 --> 00:07:53.770
Education is one thing.

00:07:53.770 --> 00:07:56.110
It's the accumulation of
a lot of knowledge.

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:58.680
Probably sometimes encyclopedic
knowledge.

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:02.750
But is many times or most of
the times, still after 150

00:08:02.750 --> 00:08:05.400
years of Industrial Revolution,
is still is a very

00:08:05.400 --> 00:08:08.370
active person, which is the
teacher, and a very passive

00:08:08.370 --> 00:08:10.830
person, which is the student,
listening to what they're

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:12.070
talking about.

00:08:12.070 --> 00:08:15.420
Learning is about taking into
your own hands more the

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:18.240
destiny, and being the architect
of your own destiny.

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:21.230
And if you do that from the very
beginning, we can really

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:23.280
accomplish tremendous
miracles.

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:27.140
And in order to do that writing
code is, I shouldn't

00:08:27.140 --> 00:08:30.380
be talking about this to you
guys, but writing code for the

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:33.260
rest of the world is not
understood yet as a basic

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:35.600
element of learning.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:42.409
And also programming and
constructionism, what we then

00:08:42.409 --> 00:08:46.920
develop after the basic concept
of writing code, how a

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:51.980
child of five years of age,
could build his own knowledge

00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:55.870
base by building, by doing.

00:08:55.870 --> 00:08:59.900
And that's when Seymour came
up with this already well

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:03.810
known application called the
Logo language, which is a

00:09:03.810 --> 00:09:08.130
language that allows a child of
five years of age to write

00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:09.830
code in linear programming.

00:09:09.830 --> 00:09:13.880
Something that for us, the
pre-generation, required for

00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:16.950
us to have known algebra, then
calculus, and then physics.

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:20.080
Nowadays with that language
this could be done.

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:21.700
This was written in 1980.

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:27.660
And has been the basic element
of our pedagogical ideas.

00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:31.380
And that is embedded now in
three iterations which is

00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:35.430
called Scratch, is called EToys
and TurtleArt, depending

00:09:35.430 --> 00:09:37.230
on the age and the complexity
of the child

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:38.720
that is using them.

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:41.000
But these are the cornerstone
of our

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.160
entire pedagogical element.

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:46.920
Then we started in 1982
in three countries.

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:49.760
We started in Colombia
as you saw before.

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:52.590
When Nicholas working in
France with President

00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:54.920
Mitterand, [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:58.860
creating what was called at
the time the [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:58.860 --> 00:10:01.580
It was a pioneer work
in trying to get

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:03.310
children to use computers.

00:10:03.310 --> 00:10:05.870
And then we went to Senegal,
in Africa.

00:10:05.870 --> 00:10:09.070
And then we went to
Pakistan, in Asia.

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:12.320
And that has been the most
important element of the

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:14.400
experience that we have had.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:18.630
Then in 2001 in Cambodia,
Nicholas and his family-- his

00:10:18.630 --> 00:10:20.600
son and his former wife--

00:10:20.600 --> 00:10:23.300
saw this little village that has
been very much published.

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:25.620
And you can see it in "60
Minutes" also, because there

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:27.780
was a big segment in "60
Minutes" about this little

00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:30.790
village in which there was no
electricity, no telephone, no

00:10:30.790 --> 00:10:32.720
running water, nothing.

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:37.100
And Nicholas took a big screen,
a satellite dish, and

00:10:37.100 --> 00:10:39.970
he took a little generator.

00:10:39.970 --> 00:10:42.530
And all these children
started--

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:47.490
and the first word that they
learned how to say was Google.

00:10:47.490 --> 00:10:50.000
That was very important because
they immediately

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.560
started investigating Google.

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:54.660
And that was one of the ideas
that Nicholas brought to

00:10:54.660 --> 00:10:56.180
Sergey and Larry.

00:10:56.180 --> 00:10:58.520
And that's how they became
involved with us

00:10:58.520 --> 00:11:00.210
five years later on.

00:11:00.210 --> 00:11:01.935
This is a school nowadays
that is emblematic.

00:11:01.935 --> 00:11:03.795
There are five of them
right now in Cambodia

00:11:03.795 --> 00:11:05.550
in very remote villages.

00:11:05.550 --> 00:11:10.200
And you should take a look
at their websites in "60

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:12.010
Minutes."

00:11:12.010 --> 00:11:19.750
So that idea in Cambodia gave
birth to our idea that if this

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:23.460
is working in Cambodia, it
should work worldwide.

00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:29.070
And the blocking element was the
lack of access of a child

00:11:29.070 --> 00:11:32.370
to computational capacity at
prices they could afford.

00:11:32.370 --> 00:11:35.560
At that time a laptop
was over a $1,000.

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:39.360
And we thought that we should
reduce at least to 1/10 the

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:42.620
value of a laptop, in order to
be able to really go to the

00:11:42.620 --> 00:11:44.150
base of the pyramid.

00:11:44.150 --> 00:11:48.530
So that's how the famous, or
infamous, name of the $100

00:11:48.530 --> 00:11:50.090
laptop came to be.

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:52.570
It was not that we had already
designed the laptop.

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:55.210
It was that that was the order
of magnitude that we thought

00:11:55.210 --> 00:11:58.980
was needed in order to really
be able to break the barrier

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:01.960
between massive scaling
of access to

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:03.320
computational capacity.

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:04.960
And not being able to do so.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:08.990
And also because then in 2005,
Internet was becoming really

00:12:08.990 --> 00:12:09.910
more ubiquitous.

00:12:09.910 --> 00:12:13.110
And it was not, as we did 35
years ago which was very

00:12:13.110 --> 00:12:13.780
rudimentary--

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:14.980
telephone lines--

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:20.080
that took forever to
transmit words.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:24.500
Then Nicholas presented these
with Kofi Annan of the United

00:12:24.500 --> 00:12:29.200
Nations, at the ITU
meeting in Libya.

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:32.500
And it became an instant success
in terms of concept.

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:35.400
The concept was so powerful.

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:38.010
Curiously enough it was more
powerful because of the little

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:39.900
yellow crank, than
anything else.

00:12:39.900 --> 00:12:41.820
But that would remain.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:45.240
Because we can charge the
battery with a crank, as the

00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:47.300
radios in South Africa do.

00:12:47.300 --> 00:12:51.880
But it was such a thing that
everybody became enchanted.

00:12:51.880 --> 00:12:53.420
And many presidents
of countries

00:12:53.420 --> 00:12:55.030
started to talk to us.

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:57.490
And then we decided
to launch it.

00:12:57.490 --> 00:12:59.190
So what have we done?

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:02.840
We converted a crisis into
opportunities because of the

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:05.160
problems that we faced in those
areas of the world.

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:06.430
And this is the computer
at that

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:08.090
time, as what was presented.

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:10.540
But this is the computer of
today, as you know very well,

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:12.750
because you have seen it
all over the place.

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:17.110
When you see a photo like this
you understand that something

00:13:17.110 --> 00:13:20.290
transformational has happened
to the mind of a child.

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:22.410
When you see the amount of
concentration, when you see

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:25.100
the amount of devotion, and the
amount of time that they

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:29.830
play today, and again this is
seven years ago, you might

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:32.240
think that this is obvious
because of the iPads, and the

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:35.550
Nexus, and the other tablets
that we have in place.

00:13:35.550 --> 00:13:39.180
But at that time it was
unbelievable for a person to

00:13:39.180 --> 00:13:43.310
understand how much these could
be an attractive element

00:13:43.310 --> 00:13:44.900
of learning.

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:46.730
We end the isolation as well.

